.TH scale_what_if_current  22.14 "Fri Oct 06 02:12:27 2023" 
.SH Name \fBscale_what_if_current\fR \-  Scales current to do what-if analysis for a hierarchical partition and assess its effect on IR drop
.SH Syntax  \fBscale_what_if_current\fR   [-help]   [-hierarchy <hier_name> | -region <x1 y1 x2 y2> | -global | -inst_list <filename>]   [-scale_clock_network]  [-scale <value> | -current <value>]  [-net <net_name>]  [-reset] 
.P Scales current to do what-if analysis for a hierarchical partition and assess its effect on IR drop. 
.SH Parameters    "\fB-current <value>\fR" Specifies current value in Amperes. This is used as target peak current for the given hierarchy and is then scaled appropriately. You cannot specify this option with -region <x1 y1 x2 y2> or -global options.  "\fB-global\fR" Specifies current scaling to be applied to entire design.  "\fB-help\fR" Outputs a brief description that includes the type and default information for each scale_what_if_current parameter.  For a detailed description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command man scale_what_if_current.  "\fB-hierarchy <hier_name>\fR" Specifies the name of the hierarchical block. For example, -hierarchy top/blockA. To specify global scaling for the design use "/". For example, -hierarchy /  -hierarchy is a required parameter. This parameter allows instance-based current scaling by the specified scale factor. The parameter can be used to scale down peak current values.  The use model of instance current scaling is:  scale_what_if_current -hierarchy <<instance_name>> -scale <<value>>  "\fB-net <net_name>\fR" Scales current of the specified net.   "\fB-inst_list <filename>\fR" Specifies to scale current for the specified nets. This parameter allows you to specify a file containing the list of instances and their scale factor.  Use Model  scale_what_if_current -inst_list <filename> -scale <val>  The format of <filename> is:  <instanceName> <scaleFactor>  <instanceName> <scaleFactor>  Here,
.RS  "*" 2 <val> means the global scale factor. This value will be used if the local or instance-specific scale factor is not specified.  "*" 2 <scaleFactor> means the local scale factor. If both global and local scale factors are specified, the local scale factor takes precedence.
.RE   Default scale factor value is 1.  "\fB-region <x1 y1 x2 y2>\fR" Specifies a region where current scaling is to be applied. The default unit of x and y coordinates is in microns (um).  "\fB-reset\fR" Resets all the previous scale_what_if_current command settings.  "\fB-scale <value>\fR" Specifies any value greater than 0. For example, a value of 0.5 will scale the current in half.  This is a required parameter.  "\fB-scale_clock_network \fR" When specified, scales current for all instances within the given hierarchy.  When not specified, the software does not scale the instances that belong to the clock network. It scales current for the rest of the instances within the given hierarchy to the specified value.  You cannot specify this option with -region <x1 y1 x2 y2> or -global options.  This is an optional parameter. 
.SH Examples
.RS  "*" 2  The following command scales current for the hierarchical block BLOCK_C:  scale_what_if_current -hierarchy top/BLOCK_C -current 0.5
.RE 
.SH Related Information
.RS  "*" 2 scale_what_if_capacitance  "*" 2 scale_what_if_resistance  "*" 2 create_current_region   "*" 2 "What-If Rail Analysis" in the Voltus IC Power Integrity Solution User Guide
.RE
.P
